{"title_page": "Hay Bridge, New South Wales", "text_new": "[[File:Hay Bridge over Murrumbidgee River (Leader, Melbourne, Sat 3 Oct 1908 Page 28).jpg|thumb|Hay Bridge in 1908. (Unknown Photographer. Published in the Leader, Melbourne, 3 Oct. 1908, Page 28.)|222x222px]]\nHay Bridge was a swing bridge that carryed road traffic across the [[Murrumbidgee River]] at [[Hay, New South Wales|Hay]], New South Wales, form 1873 to 1973.\n\nThe bridge consisted of two fixed and two swing spans. It was of a [[lattice girder]] design, with timber decking  The drum was a composite of cast and wrought iron that was carried on the centre pier. The opening of the bridge was operated by hand.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/about/environment/protecting-heritage/moveable-span-bridge-study-volume-2-bascule-and-swing-span-bridges-part-2.pdf|title=Volume 2: Bascule and Swing Span Bridges - Movable Span Bridge Study|last=GHD|first=|date=|website=|pages=144, 147, 148, 149|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The bridge was opened to allow [[List of Murray\u2013Darling steamboats|riverboats]] to pass the bridge. \n\nThe swing spans were each of 60 feet in length. The swinging spans turned on a pier in the centre of the river, The lower portion of the central pier was cast iron and 13 feet in diameter; it continued 20 feet below the bed of the river. The upper portion of the central pier was wrought iron, 12 feet in diameter, and 29 feet in height, with an ornamental moulding on top; within this was the iron rack on which a pinion gear allowed the swing span to the opened by one person.The pivot shaft was 8 feet long and 8-inches in diameter. The upper part of the central pier was fitted with adjusting screws to regulate weights, and carried the gearing and platform used to turn the bridge.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe piers for the side spans each consisted of a pair of  cylinders, each 6 feet in diameter of cast and wrought iron. All the piers were filled with brickwork and concrete and braced together with iron rivets. The piers of the side span had  adjusting screws for equalising the heights of swing and fixed spans. The roadway of side spans was 17 feet wide , and over swing spans was 15 feet to allow for wrought-iron cantilevers to be accommodated.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe contractors for the ironwork were [[Peter Nicol Russell|P. N. Russell and Co]]. and the sinking and fixing of the piers was by the N.S.W. Government under Mr. K. A. Franklin.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13345068|title=THE PREMIER AT HAY.|date=1874-09-08|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=5}}</ref> P. N.Russell and Co.won the tender for the iron bridgework in January 1870<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article223285633|title=Government Gazette Tenders and Contracts|date=1870-01-28|work=New South Wales Government Gazette (Sydney, NSW : 1832 - 1900)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=232}}</ref> and the cylinders for the piers were cast at their works in Sydney during 1870.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article63617555|title=OPENING OF MESSRS. P. N. RUSSELL'S NEW RAILWAY CARRIAGE FACTORY|date=1870-03-17|work=Illustrated Sydney News (NSW : 1853 - 1872)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=1}}</ref> There was a separate contract for the approaches, which was the last piece of work to be finished. Construction began around September 1871<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18757032|title=GENERAL NEWS.|date=1871-09-07|work=Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser (NSW : 1843 - 1893)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=3}}</ref> and all work was completed in 1873.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe bridge was officially opened by the Premier of New South Wales, [[Henry Parkes|Sir Henry Parkes]], on 31 August 1874, when he named the new bridge the \"Hay Bridge\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5877578|title=MR. PARKES IN RIVERINA.|date=1874-09-01|work=Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1957)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=6}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />[[File:HayMurrumbidgeeRiverBridge.JPG|thumb|The modern bridge across the Murrumbidgee River at Hay.|222x222px]]A toll was payable for using the bridge up to 1890.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140470419|title=ABOLITION OF THE HAY BRIDGE TOLLS.|date=1890-07-01|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> The bridge had a permanent caretaker whose job was to keep up the opening mechanism and open the bridge when needed to allow river traffic to pass.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141023206|title=HAY MUNICIPAL COUNCIL.|date=1920-12-10|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=4}}</ref>\n\nEven before the bridge opened, two riverboats had minor collisions with it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article113592419|title=DENILIQUIN.|date=1872-09-28|work=Riverine Herald (Echuca, Vic. : Moama, NSW : 1869 - 1954; 1998 - 2002)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> In 1906, the river steamer ''William Davies'' was involved in an accident while passing the bridge.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article145030016|title=Steamer Accident at Hay Bridge.|date=1906-09-29|work=Wagga Wagga Advertiser (NSW : 1875 - 1910)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> There were also an extraordinary number of serious traffic accidents on the bridge and its approaches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140000413|title=SERIOUS ACCIDENT ON THE HAY BRIDGE.|date=1895-03-29|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137215683|title=DAMAGES CLAIM FOLLOWS CAR ACCIDENT|date=1953-03-20|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article139811753|title=Sensational Motor Accident|date=1940-05-28|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article134751282|title=CAR ACCIDENT.|date=1912-05-22|work=Riverina Recorder (Balranald, Moulamein, NSW : 1887 - 1944)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=4}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137217490|title=TRUCK BREAKS BRIDGE FENCING.|date=1954-09-21|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref>Some of these were put down to the poor condition of the bridge roadway,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140127971|title=No title|date=1923-01-16|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> which was very narrow for motor traffic.\n\nIn 1931, the opening mechanism of the old bridge had broken and the steamboat ''[[PS Pevensey]]'' had to pull the span open and then pull it closed again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140664229|title=THE HAY BRIDGE.|date=1931-07-31|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> By the 1930s river traffic on the Murrumbidgee was in decline. The swing span was locked in 1937.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Hay Bridge was demolished in 1973 and replaced with a modern concrete bridge. The turntable of the old bridge was relocated to the Lions Park in Hay.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Road infrastructure in regional New South Wales|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Murrumbidgee River]]\n[[Category:Hay, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Bridges in the Riverina]]\n[[Category:1873 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:1973 disestablishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Hay Bridge over Murrumbidgee River (Leader, Melbourne, Sat 3 Oct 1908 Page 28).jpg|thumb|Hay Bridge in 1908. (Unknown Photographer. Published in the Leader, Melbourne, 3 Oct. 1908, Page 28.)|222x222px]]\nHay Bridge was a swing bridge that carryed road traffic across the [[Murrumbidgee River]] at [[Hay, New South Wales|Hay]], New South Wales, form 1873 to 1973.\n\nThe bridge consisted of two fixed and two swing spans. It was of a [[lattice girder]] design, with timber decking  The drum was a composite of cast and wrought iron that was carried on the centre pier. The opening of the bridge was operated by hand.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/about/environment/protecting-heritage/moveable-span-bridge-study-volume-2-bascule-and-swing-span-bridges-part-2.pdf|title=Volume 2: Bascule and Swing Span Bridges - Movable Span Bridge Study|last=GHD|first=|date=|website=|pages=144, 147, 148, 149|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The bridge was opened to allow [[List of Murray\u2013Darling steamboats|riverboats]] to pass the bridge. \n\nThe swing spans were each of 60 feet in length. The swinging spans turned on a pier in the centre of the river, The lower portion of the central pier was cast iron and 13 feet in diameter; it continued 20 feet below the bed of the river. The upper portion of the central pier was wrought iron, 12 feet in diameter, and 29 feet in height, with an ornamental moulding on top; within this was the iron rack on which a pinion gear allowed the swing span to the opened by one person.The pivot shaft was 8 feet long and 8-inches in diameter. The upper part of the central pier was fitted with adjusting screws to regulate weights, and carried the gearing and platform used to turn the bridge.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe piers for the side spans each consisted of a pair of  cylinders, each 6 feet in diameter of cast and wrought iron. All the piers were filled with brickwork and concrete and braced together with iron rivets. The piers of the side span had  adjusting screws for equalising the heights of swing and fixed spans. The roadway of side spans was 17 feet wide , and over swing spans was 15 feet to allow for wrought-iron cantilevers to be accommodated.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe contractors for the ironwork were [[Peter Nicol Russell|P. N. Russell and Co]]. and the sinking and fixing of the piers was by the N.S.W. Government under Mr. K. A. Franklin.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13345068|title=THE PREMIER AT HAY.|date=1874-09-08|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=5}}</ref> P. N.Russell and Co.won the tender for the iron bridgework in January 1870<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article223285633|title=Government Gazette Tenders and Contracts|date=1870-01-28|work=New South Wales Government Gazette (Sydney, NSW : 1832 - 1900)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=232}}</ref> and the cylinders for the piers were cast at their works in Sydney during 1870.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article63617555|title=OPENING OF MESSRS. P. N. RUSSELL'S NEW RAILWAY CARRIAGE FACTORY|date=1870-03-17|work=Illustrated Sydney News (NSW : 1853 - 1872)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=1}}</ref> There was a separate contract for the approaches, which was the last piece of work to be finished. Construction began around September 1871<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18757032|title=GENERAL NEWS.|date=1871-09-07|work=Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser (NSW : 1843 - 1893)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=3}}</ref> and all work was completed in 1873.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe bridge was officially opened by the Premier of New South Wales, [[Henry Parkes|Sir Henry Parkes]], on 31 August 1874, when he named the new bridge the \"Hay Bridge\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article5877578|title=MR. PARKES IN RIVERINA.|date=1874-09-01|work=Argus (Melbourne, Vic. : 1848 - 1957)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=6}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />[[File:HayMurrumbidgeeRiverBridge.JPG|thumb|The modern bridge across the Murrumbidgee River at Hay.|222x222px]]A toll was payable for using the bridge up to 1890.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140470419|title=ABOLITION OF THE HAY BRIDGE TOLLS.|date=1890-07-01|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> The bridge had a permanent caretaker whose job was to keep up the opening mechanism and open the bridge when needed to allow river traffic to pass.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141023206|title=HAY MUNICIPAL COUNCIL.|date=1920-12-10|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=4}}</ref>\n\nEven before the bridge opened, two riverboats had minor collisions with it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article113592419|title=DENILIQUIN.|date=1872-09-28|work=Riverine Herald (Echuca, Vic. : Moama, NSW : 1869 - 1954; 1998 - 2002)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> In 1906, the river steamer ''William Davies'' was involved in an accident while passing the bridge.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article145030016|title=Steamer Accident at Hay Bridge.|date=1906-09-29|work=Wagga Wagga Advertiser (NSW : 1875 - 1910)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> There were also an extraordinary number of serious traffic accidents on the bridge and its approaches.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140000413|title=SERIOUS ACCIDENT ON THE HAY BRIDGE.|date=1895-03-29|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137215683|title=DAMAGES CLAIM FOLLOWS CAR ACCIDENT|date=1953-03-20|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article139811753|title=Sensational Motor Accident|date=1940-05-28|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article134751282|title=CAR ACCIDENT.|date=1912-05-22|work=Riverina Recorder (Balranald, Moulamein, NSW : 1887 - 1944)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=4}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article137217490|title=TRUCK BREAKS BRIDGE FENCING.|date=1954-09-21|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref>Some of these were put down to the poor condition of the bridge roadway,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140127971|title=No title|date=1923-01-16|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> which was very narrow for motor traffic.\n\nIn 1931, the opening mechanism of the old bridge had broken and the steamboat ''[[PS Pevensey]]'' had to pull the span open and then pull it closed again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article140664229|title=THE HAY BRIDGE.|date=1931-07-31|work=Riverine Grazier (Hay, NSW : 1873 - 1954)|access-date=2020-04-08|pages=2}}</ref> By the 1930s river traffic on the Murrumbidgee was in decline. The swing span was locked in 1937.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Hay Bridge was demolished in 1973 and replaced with a modern concrete bridge. The turntable of the old bridge was relocated to the Lions Park in Hay.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n\n[[Category:Murrumbidgee River]]\n[[Category:Hay, New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Bridges in the Riverina]]\n[[Category:1873 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:1973 disestablishments in Australia]]\n<references />\n", "name_user": "Rangasyd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Road infrastructure in regional New South Wales", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hay_Bridge,_New_South_Wales"}
{"title_page": "Jim Frazier (politician)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2020}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n|name           = Jim Frazier\n|image          = Jim Frazier of the California State Assembly (2012).jpg\n|alt            = \n|state_assembly = California\n|district       = [[California's 11th State Assembly district|11th]]\n|term_start     = December 3, 2012\n|term_end       = \n|predecessor    = ''new district''\n|successor      = \n|birth_name     = James Leroy Frazier, Jr.\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1959|05|04}}\n|birth_place    = [[Martinez, California]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|nationality    = [[United States|American]]\n|party          = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse         = \n|children       =  2\n|residence      = [[Discovery Bay, California]]\n|alma_mater     = \n|occupation     = \n|profession     = [[Small business]]man\n|religion       = \n|signature      = \n|website        = \n|footnotes      = \n}}\n\n'''James L. Frazier Jr.''' (born May 4, 1959) is an [[United States|American]] [[politician]] currently serving in the [[California State Assembly]]. He is a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] representing the [[California's 11th State Assembly district|11th Assembly District]], which encompasses eastern [[Contra Costa County]], southern [[Solano County]] and a small portion of rural [[Sacramento County]].\n\nPrior to being elected to the Assembly in 2012, he was an [[Oakley, California|Oakley]] City Councilmember and [[Mayor]].\n\n== Legislative career ==\n\nDuring his first term, Frazier's legislation focused on roadway safety and infrastructure.  He authored Assembly Bill 1113, concerning provisional driver's licenses, which sought to strengthen teen driver-licensing programs and improve the safety of the roadways.  He also authored Assembly Bill 417, which lessened the processes needed to authorize bike lanes in urbanized areas.  He authored Assembly Bill 513, which expands the use of [[rubberized asphalt]] (made from [[waste tires]]) in roads and other transportation projects. And he authored Assembly Bill 1336, which provides the state with added enforcement powers necessary to ensure that workers are paid mandated wages.<ref>{{cite news |title=Assemblyman Jim Frazier's legislation still on governor's desk |url=http://www.thereporter.com/general-news/20130926/assemblyman-jim-fraziers-legislation-still-on-governors-desk |newspaper=[[The Reporter (Vacaville)|The Reporter]] |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=March 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2014-15 legislative session, Frazier served as Chair of the Assembly Transportation Committee. In this role, he contributed to the defeat of a bill seeking to explicitly add representation from disadvantaged communities to the [[California Transportation Commission]], stating that \"the bill would elevate disadvantaged communities and their interests above all others, and we can\u2019t have that.\" <ref name=\"Streetsblog_0317\">{{cite news |title=Transportation Equity Bills Defeated in Assembly Transpo Committee |url=http://cal.streetsblog.org/2016/04/19/transportation-equity-bills-defeated-in-assembly-transpo-committee/ |newspaper=Streetsblog Cal |date=April 19, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2017 |author=Melanie Curry}}</ref>\n\n==2014 California State Assembly ==\n{{see also|California State Assembly elections, 2014}}\n\n{{Election box open primary begin no change\n| title = [[California's 11th State Assembly district]] election, 2014\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Jim Frazier ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 30,893\n| percentage = 60.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Alex Henthorn\n| votes = 20,002\n| percentage = 39.3\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 50,895\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box open primary general election no change}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Jim Frazier ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 54,044\n| percentage = 59.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Alex Henthorn\n| votes = 36,475\n| percentage = 40.3\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 90,519\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner = California Democratic Party\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==2016 California State Assembly ==\n{{see also|California State Assembly election, 2016}}\n{{Election box open primary begin no change\n| title = [[California's 11th State Assembly district]] election, 2016\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Jim Frazier ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 62,952\n| percentage = 65.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Dave Miller\n| votes = 32,545\n| percentage = 34.1\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 95,497\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box open primary general election no change}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Jim Frazier ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 111,592\n| percentage = 64.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Dave Miller\n| votes = 62,227\n| percentage = 35.8\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 173,819\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner = California Democratic Party\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==2018 California State Assembly ==\n{{see also|California State Assembly election, 2018}}\n{{Election box open primary begin no change\n| title = [[California's 11th State Assembly district]] election, 2018\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = [[Jim Frazier (politician)|Jim Frazier]] ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 39095\n| percentage = 48.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Lisa Romero\n| votes = 30623\n| percentage = 37.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Diane Stewart\n| votes = 11224\n| percentage = 13.9\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 80942\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box open primary general election no change}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = [[Jim Frazier (politician)|Jim Frazier]] ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 96254\n| percentage = 61.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Lisa Romero\n| votes = 60335\n| percentage = 38.5\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 156589\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner = California Democratic Party\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n==2020 California State Assembly ==\n{{Election box open primary begin no change\n| title = 2020 [[California's 11th State Assembly district]] election\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = [[Jim Frazier (politician)|Jim Frazier]] ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 74,950\n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Debra Schwab ([[Write-in candidate|write in]])\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100%\n}}\n{{Election box open primary general election no change}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = [[Jim Frazier (politician)|Jim Frazier]] ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Debra Schwab\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://asmdc.org/members/a11/}}\n* [http://www.peoplebeforepolitics.org/ Campaign website]\n\n{{California State Assembly}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frazier, Jim}}\n[[Category:Members of the California State Assembly]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in California]]\n[[Category:California city council members]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Martinez, California]]\n[[Category:People from Oakley, California]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2020}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n|name           = Jim Frazier\n|image          = Jim Frazier of the California State Assembly (2012).jpg\n|alt            = \n|state_assembly = California\n|district       = [[California's 11th State Assembly district|11th]]\n|term_start     = December 3, 2012\n|term_end       = \n|predecessor    = ''new district''\n|successor      = \n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1959|05|04}}\n|birth_place    = [[Martinez, California]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|nationality    = [[United States|American]]\n|party          = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse         = \n|children       = \n|residence      = [[Discovery Bay, California]]\n|alma_mater     = \n|occupation     = \n|profession     = [[Small business]]man\n|religion       = \n|signature      = \n|website        = \n|footnotes      = \n}}\n\n'''James L. Frazier Jr.''' (born May 4, 1959) is an [[United States|American]] [[politician]] currently serving in the [[California State Assembly]]. He is a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] representing the [[California's 11th State Assembly district|11th Assembly District]], which encompasses East Contra Costa County, Solano County and a portion of rural Sacramento County.\n\nPrior to being elected to the Assembly in 2012, he was an [[Oakley, California|Oakley]] City Councilmember and [[Mayor]].\n\n== Legislative career ==\n\nDuring his first term, Frazier's legislation focused on roadway safety and infrastructure.  He authored Assembly Bill 1113, concerning provisional driver's licenses, which sought to strengthen teen driver-licensing programs and improve the safety of the roadways.  He also authored Assembly Bill 417, which lessened the processes needed to authorize bike lanes in urbanized areas.  He authored Assembly Bill 513, which expands the use of [[rubberized asphalt]] (made from [[waste tires]]) in roads and other transportation projects. And he authored Assembly Bill 1336, which provides the state with added enforcement powers necessary to ensure that workers are paid mandated wages.<ref>{{cite news |title=Assemblyman Jim Frazier's legislation still on governor's desk |url=http://www.thereporter.com/general-news/20130926/assemblyman-jim-fraziers-legislation-still-on-governors-desk |newspaper=[[The Reporter (Vacaville)|The Reporter]] |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=March 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2014-15 legislative session, Frazier served as Chair of the Assembly Transportation Committee. In this role, he contributed to the defeat of a bill seeking to explicitly add representation from disadvantage communities to the [[California Transportation Commission]], stating that \"the bill would elevate disadvantaged communities and their interests above all others, and we can\u2019t have that.\" <ref name=\"Streetsblog_0317\">{{cite news |title=Transportation Equity Bills Defeated in Assembly Transpo Committee |url=http://cal.streetsblog.org/2016/04/19/transportation-equity-bills-defeated-in-assembly-transpo-committee/ |newspaper=Streetsblog Cal |date=April 19, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2017 |author=Melanie Curry}}</ref>\n\n==2014 California State Assembly ==\n{{see also|California State Assembly elections, 2014}}\n\n{{Election box open primary begin no change\n| title = [[California's 11th State Assembly district]] election, 2014\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Jim Frazier ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 30,893\n| percentage = 60.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Alex Henthorn\n| votes = 20,002\n| percentage = 39.3\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 50,895\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box open primary general election no change}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Jim Frazier ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 54,044\n| percentage = 59.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Republican Party\n| candidate = Alex Henthorn\n| votes = 36,475\n| percentage = 40.3\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 90,519\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner = California Democratic Party\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==2016 California State Assembly ==\n{{see also|California State Assembly election, 2016}}\n{{Election box open primary begin no change\n| title = [[California's 11th State Assembly district]] election, 2016\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = California Democratic Party\n| candidate = Jim Frazier ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 62,952\n| percentage = 65.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Californ