rch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFrantisek was the older brother of Anezka.\n|\n|-\n|30 August 1906\n[[SS Rhein (1899)|SS Rhein]]\n[[Bremen]][[File:USS_Susquehanna_(ID-3016).jpg|center|thumb|SS Rhein (converted to the USS Susquehanna)]]\n|11 September 1906\n[[Baltimore]]\n|Hurtak - Matej (1892-1964)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:2CSK-F6T|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Hurtak|first=|date=1906|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nKoncal - Matej (1885-1976)\n|\n|-\n|\n|c. 1907\n|Knez - Frantisek (1885-1965)\n|\n|-\n|29 August 1907\n[[SS Rhein (1899)|SS Rhein]]\n[[Bremen]][[File:USS_Susquehanna_(ID-3016).jpg|center|thumb|SS Rhein (converted to the USS Susquehanna)]]\n|12 September 1907\n[[Baltimore]]\n|Klecka - Marie (1892-)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:2CSL-C47|title=Maryland, Baltimore Passenger Lists, 1820-1948|last=Klecka|first=|date=1907|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|8 February 1910\n[[SS George Washington]]\n\n[[Bremen]][[File:George Washington Dampfer.jpg|center|thumb|195x195px]]<br />\n|18 February 1910\n[[Ellis Island|New York]]\n|Hlavac - Ludmila (1875-1957) [with her citizen husband Frantisek Kral from Louzna and 5 of their children]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JJXX-H38|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Hlavac|first=|date=1910|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMares - Filomena (1894-1960)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JJXX-H3J|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Mares|first=|date=1910|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFilomena was the younger sister of Marie.\n|\n|-\n|11 February 1911\n[[SS George Washington]]\n\n[[Bremen]][[File:George Washington Dampfer.jpg|center|thumb|195x195px]]<br />\n|20 February 1911\n[[Ellis Island|New York]]\n|Skala - Marie (1891-1925)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JJV5-PMX|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Skala|first=|date=1911|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|13 December 1913\n[[SS George Washington]]\n\n[[Bremen]][[File:George Washington Dampfer.jpg|center|thumb|195x195px]]<br />\n|22 December 1913\n\n[[Ellis Island|New York]]\n|Behensky - Josef (1898-1974)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JNTV-R5Q|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Behensky|first=|date=1913|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nSkala - Anna (1889-1946)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:JNTV-Y2K|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Skala|first=|date=1913|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nJosef was the younger brother of Vaclav. Anna was the older sister of Marie.\n|\n|-\n|7 December 1920\n[[SS La Touraine]]\n\n[[Le Havre]][[File:SS La Touraine.jpg|center|thumb]]<br />\n|17 December 1920\n[[Ellis Island|New York]]\n|Popule - Marie (1904-1992)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:J6HD-Y62|title=New York Passenger Arrival Lists (Ellis Island), 1892-1924|last=Popule|first=|date=1920|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMarie was the niece of Marie Populova.\n|\n|-\n|4 May 1947\n[[RMS Queen Elizabeth]]\n\n[[Southampton]][[File:RMS Queen Elizabeth Southampton.jpg|center|thumb|At port in Southampton]]<br />\n|9 May 1947\n[[New York City|New York]]\n|Moutvic - Barbora (1893-)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:24PN-FMB|title=New York, New York Passenger and Crew Lists, 1909, 1925-1957|last=Moutvic|first=|date=1947|website=FamilySearch|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nShe had a family in [[Prague]] and was probably only visiting her brother Karel.\n|\n|-\n|\n|before 1952\n|Mares - Frantisek (1920-2001)\n\nFrantisek was the nephew of Marie and Filomena Maresova.\n|\n|}\n\n== Population ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Population\n|-\n|1880\n|344<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426168|title=Census 1880 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo), Nr. 47 {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|1890\n|293<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426169/soap-kt_01159_census-sum-1890-nehodiv_0030?x=-40&y=268&w=541&h=239|title=Census 1890 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo) - souhrn / Sammelbogen {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1900\n|306<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426219/soap-kt_01159_census-sum-1900-nehodiv_0160?x=260&y=69&w=680&h=301|title=Census 1900 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo) - souhrn / Sammelbogen {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1910\n|291<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426270/soap-kt_01159_census-sum-1910-nehodiv_0020?x=229&y=-2&w=813&h=360|title=Census 1910 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo) - souhrn / Sammelbogen {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|1921\n|262<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.portafontium.eu/iipimage/34426372?x=-57&y=437&w=1092&h=581|title=Census 1921 Nehodiv (Nehodiw, Nehodivo), Nr. 52 {{!}} Porta fontium|website=www.portafontium.eu|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n|-\n|28&nbsp;August 2006\n|79\n|}\n\n== Facts ==\nThere is a chapel with a computer-controlled bell in the center of the village. There is also a limestone quarry from which white limestone is extracted. The village is towered by St\u00edrka Hill, which dominates the general area with its height of 702 m above sea level. Southwest of the village is a natural monument Dolejsi drahy .\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Nehodiv, zat\u00e1\u010dka.jpg|Houses\nFile:Nehodiv6.jpg|House\nFile:Nehodiv5.jpg|Village square with tree\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080618131004/http://www.czso.cz/lexikon/mos_vdb.nsf/okresy/CZ0322/ Czech Statistical Office: Municipalities of Klatovy District]\n\n{{commons category|Nehodiv}}\n{{Klatovy District}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Klatovy District]]\n", "name_user": "Jonnychiwa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGenealogy and Immigration to America", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nehodiv"}
{"title_page": "Kings XI Punjab", "text_new": "{{short description|Cricket team}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox cricket team\n| name            = Kings XI Punjab\n| alt_name        = \n| image           = Kings XI Punjab logo.svg\n| alt             = \n| captain         = [[K. L. Rahul]]\n| coach           = [[Anil Kumble]]\n| city            = [[Mohali]] ([[Chandigarh capital region|Chandigarh CR]]), [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[India]]\n| colors          = [[File:Kings XI Punjab colours.svg|20px|alt=KXIP|link=Kings XI Punjab]]\n| owner           = {{unbulleted list|[[Mohit Burman]] (46%)<br>[[Ness Wadia]] (23%)<br>[[Preity Zinta]] (23%)<br>[[Karan Paul]] (8%)<ref>{{cite news |title=KXIP co-owner Mohit Burman: It's Ness Wadia's personal matter and nothing to do with Kings XI franchise |url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/sport/cricket/kxip-co-owner-says-its-nesss-personal-matter/articleshow/69180420.cms |accessdate=25 December 2019 |work=Pune Mirror |date=5 May 2019}}</ref>}}\n| founded         = {{Start date|df=yes|2008}}\n| dissolved       = <!-- or | last_match = -->\n| ground         = [[Punjab Cricket Association Stadium|PCA Stadium]], [[Mohali]]<br>(Capacity: 26,000)\n| ground2         = [[Holkar Stadium]], [[Indore]] (Capacity : 30,000)\n| website         = {{URL|www.kxip.in}}\n| current         = [[Kings XI Punjab in 2020]]\n| t_pattern_la          = \n| t_pattern_b           = _collar\n| t_pattern_ra          = \n| t_pattern_pants       = \n| t_leftarm             = FF0000\n| t_body                = FF0000\n| t_rightarm            = FF0000\n| t_pants               = E7E7EC\n| t_title              = T20 kit\n}}\n\nThe '''Kings XI Punjab''' ('''KXIP''') are a franchise [[cricket]] team based in [[Mohali]] ([[Chandigarh capital region|Chandigarh CR]]), [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], that plays in the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL). Established in 2008, the franchise is jointly owned by [[Mohit Burman]], [[Ness Wadia]], [[Preity Zinta]] and [[Karan Paul]]. The team plays its home matches at the [[PCA Stadium]], Mohali. Since the [[2010 IPL]], they have been playing some of their home games at either [[HPCA Stadium|Dharamsala]] or [[Holkar Stadium|Indore]].\n\nThe Kings XI Punjab's [[catchment area]]s are [[Kashmir Valley|Kashmir]], [[Jammu Division|Jammu]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], Punjab and [[Haryana]]\u2014evident from the letter sequence \"K J H P H\" in the banner of the team's logo.<ref>{{cite web|title=What's in a logo? Ask KXIP|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/what-s-in-a-logo-ask-kxip/story-0TOCX9haDy2UdcDlZfX26L.html|publisher=[[Hindustan Times]]|accessdate=19 May 2017|date=25 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=IPL: Preity Zinta unveils Mohali-Kings XI Punjab|url=http://www.thatscricket.com/news/2008/04/01/0104preity-zinta-unveils-kings-xi-punjab.html|publisher=Thatscricket|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> Apart from the [[2014 Indian Premier League|2014 season]] when they topped the league table and finished runners-up, the team has made only one other playoff appearance in 12 seasons.\n\n==Franchise history==\nIn 2007, the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) created the cricket tournament the [[Indian Premier League]] based on the [[Twenty20]] format of the game. Franchises for eight cities were made available in an auction held in Mumbai on 20 February 2008. The team representing Punjab was bought by the [[Dabur]] group's [[Mohit Burman]] (46%), the Wadia group's [[Ness Wadia]] (23%), [[Preity Zinta]] (23%), and Saptarshi Dey of the Dey & Dey Group (minor stake). The group paid a total of $76 million to acquire the franchise.\n\n=== Expulsion from the IPL and return ===\nFollowing the controversy surrounding the BCCI and [[Lalit Modi]] in 2010, the Indian Premier League announced on 10 October 2010 that it had terminated the franchise contracts of Kings XI Punjab and the [[Rajasthan Royals]]. The teams announced that they would take legal action to remain in the Indian Premier League.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/current/story/480748.html |title=IPL news: IPL terminates Punjab, Rajasthan franchises &#124; Cricket News &#124; Global &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date= 10 October 2010|accessdate=8 August 2012}}</ref> Initially, the team tried to negotiate a solution with the league, but when one could not be reached, they decided to file a case in Mumbai High Court accusing the IPL of getting rid of the two teams so that when the bidding process started for the 2012 IPL season, the contract would be given to a more lucrative bidder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/story/486712.html|title=Kings XI Punjab move court against scrapping|date=12 November 2010|website=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref>\n\nKings XI Punjab was reinstated with the involvement of the [[High Court]].<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=QZ7OCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT62&lpg=PT62&dq=Kings+XI+franchise+reinstated#v=onepage&q=Kings%20XI%20franchise%20reinstated&f=false |title=Not Out!: The Incredible Story of The Indian Premier League By Desh Gaurav Sekhi |last=Sekhi |first=Desh Gaurav |website=books.google.ca |url-status=live |access-date=28 November 2019|isbn=9789385890949 |date=5 April 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Team history==\n\n===2008===\nThe 2008 tournament got off to a slow start for the Kings XI Punjab, with the team losing their first two games. However, 94 runs by Kumar Sangakkara helped them to win the third game. Despite the absence of [[Brett Lee]] and [[Simon Katich]] (who were committed to tour the [[West Indies]] with [[Australia]]), the team found its groove. Powered by their balanced bowling line-up<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ipl/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3519&team=4342&type=tournament|title=Indian Premier League, 2007/08 - Kings XI Punjab Cricket Team Records & Stats - ESPNcricinfo.com|website=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref> and effective top order,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ipl/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_for_any_wicket.html?id=3519&team=4342&type=tournament|title=Indian Premier League, 2007/08 - Kings XI Punjab Cricket Team Records & Stats - ESPNcricinfo.com|website=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref> the team won nine of its next 10 matches, clinching a berth in the semi-final, where their run in the tournament came to an end with a comprehensive nine-wicket loss to the [[Chennai Super Kings]].\n\n[[Shaun Marsh]] was arguably KXIP's star player in the inaugural IPL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/352688.html|title=Five finds|date=28 May 2008|website=Cricinfo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2008/20080523/sports.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Sport|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref> The opener from [[Western Australia]] was overlooked in the IPL player auctions and was signed by the franchise on 9 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/australia/content/story/345650.html|title=Shaun Marsh joins Mohali|date=9 April 2008|website=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref> He finished the tournament as the Orange Cap holder\u2014the award for the player with the most runs across the competition\u2014with an average of 68.44 and a strike rate of 139.68 in 11 innings. Marsh managed to hit one century and five half-centuries across the course of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ipl/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=3519&type=tournament|title=Indian Premier League, 2007/08 Cricket Team Records & Stats - ESPNcricinfo.com|website=[[Cricinfo]]}}</ref>\n\n===2009===\nFinishing as semi-finalists in 2008, Kings XI Punjab started with ambitions to win the trophy. These were supported by their new sponsors [[Emirates Airlines]]. With two available slots to fill, the Kings XI Punjab made bids on [[Jerome Taylor]] and [[Yusuf Abdulla]] at the second IPL auction.\n\nThe team took a hit as most of their Australian cricketers were unavailable. The team lacked available pace bowlers after Jerome Taylor backed out at the last minute with an injury.\n\nThe team lost badly to the [[Delhi Daredevils]] and the [[Kolkata Knight Riders]], however, they returned to form by beating the [[Royal Challengers]], the Rajasthan Royals and the [[Mumbai Indians]]. Then the team witnessed a roller-coaster ride in their next eight matches with four wins and four losses. The team's semi-final hopes were crushed after losing to the [[Chennai Super Kings]] in their last match.\n\n===2010===\nKings XI Punjab lost six matches to the Kolkata Knight Riders, the Delhi Daredevils, the [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]], the [[Deccan Chargers]], the Rajasthan Royals and the Mumbai Indians but managed to win a match against Chennai Super Kings when the scores were level and the match went to a Super Over. Kings XI Punjab were boosted by the return of Brett Lee against Kolkata, but he was not at his best. Shaun Marsh returned in the match against the Mumbai Indians. In spite of his good performance, which included a half century, the team lost the match. They ended IPL3 in the last position.\n\n===2011===\n\nThe 2011 IPL season looked promising when they brought a full strength team with [[Michael Bevan]] as coach and [[Adam Gilchrist]] was appointed as captain.\n\nKings XI Punjab missed out on the play offs by two points (or one victory). This meant they finished fifth in the points table.\n\n===2012===\n\nKings XI Punjab finished in sixth place overall, winning eight matches out of sixteen.\n\n===2013===\n\nKings XI Punjab failed to qualify for the play-offs, but batsman [[David Miller (cricketer)|David Miller]] played one of the innings of the tournament in the 51st match against the Royal Challengers Bangalore, as he smashed 101 off 38 deliveries and included eight fours and seven sixes. Coming in at 51\u20133 in the eighth over and chasing a target of 190, Miller rectified the game and led Punjab to a six-wicket win with two overs remaining. Adam Gilchrist retired at the end of the season.\n\n===2014===\n\nAustralia's T20I captain [[George Bailey (cricketer, born 1982)|George Bailey]] was leading the squad for the seventh season. Other buys featured the likes of [[Virender Sehwag]], [[Glenn Maxwell]] and [[Mitchell Johnson (cricketer)|Mitchell Johnson]]. Kings XI Punjab began the tournament by winning their first five games which were held outside India in UAE due to elections. The stand out player was Glenn Maxwell with his unorthodox and powerful hitting, scoring 95, 89 and 95 in his first three innings with a strike rate of over 200 who got equal contribution from South African David Miller, both of them making the side look invincible. There were many innings from the veteran Indian batsman Virender Sehwag and young star [[Manan Vohra]] which made the middle order batting easy and allowed the team to qualify for the playoffs. Due to a 122 run knock from Virender Sehwag against the Chennai Super Kings in the semifinal, KXIP made their way to the final. There they faced the Kolkata Knight Riders where they batted first and set a good target of 199 owing to [[Wriddhiman Saha]]'s 115.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/indian-premier-league-2014/news/225143-after-kolkata-knight-riders-west-bengal-plan-to-fete-ipl-final-centurion-wriddhiman-saha|title=After Kolkata Knight Riders, West Bengal Plan to Fete IPL Final Centurion Wriddhiman Saha |author=Soumitra Bose |website=[[NDTV]] |date=4 June 2014 |accessdate=10 March 2018 }}</ref> However, due to [[Manish Pandey]]'s 94 off 50 balls and his teammates' consistently high run rate, including [[Piyush Chawla]]'s 13 off five balls, KKR were able to win the final by three wickets in the final over of the match.\n\n====2014 CLT20====\n\nKings XI were placed in Group B along with the [[Hobart Hurricanes]] (Australia); the [[Barbados Tridents]] (West Indies); the [[Cape Cobras]] (South Africa) and the [[Northern Districts cricket team|Northern Knights]] (New Zealand).\n\nKings XI's first match was in their home stadium the [[PCA Stadium]], [[Mohali]] where they beat Hobart Hurricanes by five wickets, overhauling Hobart's 144\u20136 in 17.4 overs. [[Thisara Perera]] was named the Man Of The Match with 2\u201317 and 35. Glenn Maxwell top scored in the game with 43. They also won the second match beating the Barbados Tridents by four wickets. They won their third match of the competition against the [[Northern Knights]] and qualified for the semi finals. They continued to win their final group match against the Cape Cobras but were knocked out of the tournament at the semi-final stage with a disappointing defeat against their IPL rivals the Chennai Super Kings,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Match Report: SF2 - Kings XI Punjab V Chennai Super Kings|url = http://www.clt20.com/news/2014/match-reports/2364/match-report-sf2-kings-xi-punjab-v-chennai-super-kings|website = Champions League T20 |author=Arun Gopalakrishnan |location=Mumbai |date=2 October 2014 |accessdate = 21 April 2015}}</ref> who went on to win the tournament.\n\n===2015===\n\nGeorge Bailey continued to lead the side during the 2015 season. The team won just three of the 14 games and finishing eighth in the league. David Miller finished the season as top scorer with 357 runs and Anureet Singh finished the season as the top wicket taker with 15 wickets.\n\n===2016===\n\nDavid Miller and Murali Vijay captained the team in the first and second half of the 2016 season. The team finished eighth once again with only four wins. Murali Vijay was the top scorer with 453 runs and Sandeep Sharma was the top wicket taker with 15 wickets.\n\n===2017===\n\nVirender Sehwag joined as head coach as the team looked to recover from two back-to-back last-place finishes in the league. Glenn Maxwell was appointed as the captain. [[Eoin Morgan]], [[Darren Sammy]] and [[Hashim Amla]] joined the likes of David Miller in the team. The team missed out on a place in the play-offs by a last game defeat to the [[Rising Pune Supergiant]] and ended the season in fifth, winning seven out of their 14 games. Hashim Amla finished the season as top scorer with 420 runs including two centuries, and Sandeep Sharma was the top wicket taker with 17 wickets.\n\n===2018===\nThe Kings XI Punjab squad for the 2018 IPL season included internationals such as: [[Ravichandran Ashwin]], [[Yuvraj Singh]], [[KL Rahul]], [[Aaron Finch]] and [[Chris Gayle]]. Ashwin was appointed as captain and [[Brad Hodge]] as coach. The Tournament started well with KL Rahul scoring a fine fifty off 14 balls to guide KXIP home against Daredevils. Riding on KL Rahul and Chris Gayle's red hot form at the top and Andrew Tye and Mujeeb with ball, the team went on to win 6 out of their first seven games eventually becoming favourites to the title. Their weakness in Indian core was however exposed as they could manage just one win in next eight and ultimately not being qualified for playoffs despite a dream start from the beginning.\n\n===2019===\nFranchises confirmed the names of retained players for the 12th season of Indian Premier League. KXIP retained the following players for the 2019 season: KL Rahul, Chris Gayle, [[Andrew Tye]], [[Mayank Agarwal]], [[Ankit Rajpoot]], [[Mujeeb Ur Rahman]], [[Karun Nair]], David Miller and Ravichandran Ashwin. On the auction day (18 December 2018), KXIP snapped up new 13 players: Varun Chakaravarthy, [[Sam Curran]], [[Mohammed Shami]], Prabhsimran Singh, [[Nicholas Pooran]], [[Moises Henriques]], [[Hardus Viljoen]], [[Darshan Nalkande]], [[Sarfaraz Khan]], Arshdeep Singh, Agnivesh Ayachi, Harpreet Brar, and [[Murugan Ashwin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=IPL 2019 Auction: Varun Chakravarathy 'over the moon' after bagging million-dollar deal|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/sports/cricket/story/varun-chakaravarthy-ipl-2019-auction-indian-premier-league-kings-xi-punjab-1412473-2018-12-18 |website=[[India Today]]|author= |date=18 December 2018 |accessdate=18 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nKings XI Punjab ended up in sixth position in the league table. KL Rahul was the highest run scorer for the team with 593 runs in 14 matches.\n\n==Seasons==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"background:#fff; width:40%; text-align:center\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n! '''Year'''\n! League table standing\n! Final standing\n|- \n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2008|2008]]'''\n| 2nd out of 8\n|style=\"background: orange;\"| '''Semifinalists (3rd)'''\n|-\n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2009|2009]]'''\n| 5th out of 8\n| '''5th'''\n|-\n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2010|2010]]'''\n| 8th out of 8\n| '''8th'''\n|-\n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2011|2011]]'''\n| 5th out of 10\n| '''5th'''\n|-\n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2012|2012]]'''\n| 6th out of 9\n| '''6th'''\n|-\n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2013|2013]]'''\n| 6th out of 9\n| '''6th'''\n|-\n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2014|2014]]'''\n| 1st out of 8\n|style=\"background: silver;\"| '''Runners-up'''\n|-\n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2015|2015]]'''\n| 8th out of 8\n| '''8th'''\n|- \n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2016|2016]]'''\n| 8th out of 8\n| '''8th'''\n|- \n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2017|2017]]'''\n| 5th out of 8\n| '''5th'''\n|-\n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2018|2018]]'''\n| 7th out of 8\n| '''7th'''\n|-\n! '''[[Kings XI Punjab in 2019|2019]]'''\n| 6th out of 8\n| '''6th'''\n|}\n\nKings XI played in the now defunct [[Champions League Twenty20]] once, in [[2014 Champions League Twenty20|2014]] and finished as semi-finalists.\n\n== Current squad ==\n{{Kings XI Punjab Roster}}\n\n==Administration and coaching staff==\n\n* Owners - {{flagicon|IND}} [[Mohit Burman]], {{flagicon|IND}} [[Ness Wadia]], {{flagicon|IND}} [[Preity Zinta]], {{flagicon|IND}} [[Karan Paul]]\n* CEO - {{flagicon|IND}} [[Satish Menon]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Kings XI Punjab to play all home fixtures in Mohali |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/top-stories/kings-xi-punjab-to-play-all-home-fixtures-in-mohali/articleshow/72419260.cms |accessdate=25 December 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Director of cricket operations and head coach - {{flagicon|IND}} [[Anil Kumble]]<ref name=kumble>{{cite news |title=Anil Kumble Named KXIP Head Coach, Courtney Walsh Comes on Board as Scout |url=https://www.news18.com/cricketnext/news/anil-kumble-named-kxip-head-coach-courtney-walsh-comes-on-board-as-scout-2341237.html |accessdate=25 December 2019 |work=News18 |date=11 October 2019}}</ref>\n* Assistant coach - {{flagicon|ZIM}} [[Andy Flower]]<ref name=flower/>\n* Batting coach - {{flagicon|IND}} [[Wasim Jaffer]]<ref name=jaffer>{{cite news |title=IPL: Kings XI Punjab appoints Wasim Jaffer as batting coach |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/ipl-kings-xi-punjab-wasim-jaffer-batting-coach-anil-kumble-sunil-joshi-jonty-rhodes/article30345830.ece |accessdate=25 December 2019 |work=Sportstar |date=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Bowling coach - {{flagicon|RSA}} [[Charl Langeveldt]]<ref name=flower>{{cite news |last1=Acharya |first1=Shayan |title=IPL 2020: Andy Flower named Kings XI Punjab's assistant coach |url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket/ipl/ipl-news/kings-xi-punjab-assistant-andy-flower-anil-kumble-sunil-joshi/article31010331.ece |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=Sportstar |date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n* Fielding coach - {{flagicon|SA}} [[Jonty Rhodes]]<ref name=jaffer/>\n* Team physio - {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Andrew Leipus]]<ref name=flower/>\n* Trainer - {{flagicon|SA}} Adrian Le Roux<ref name=flower/>\n\n==Head coaches==\n\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Tom Moody]]- 2008\u20132010\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Michael Bevan]] - 2011\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Adam Gilchrist]] - 2012\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Darren Lehmann]] - 2013\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Sanjay Bangar]] - 2014\u20132016\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Virender Sehwag]] - 2017\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Brad Hodge]] - 2018\n* {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Mike Hesson]] - 2019\n* 